orization2star  aThe essays in this book analyze and explain the crisis of democratic representation in five Andean countries: Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, and Venezuela. In this region, disaffection with democracy, political parties, and legislatures has spread to an alarming degree. Many presidents have been forced from office, and many traditional parties have fallen by the wayside. These five countries have the potential to be negative examples in a region that has historically had strong demonstration and diffusion effects in terms of regime changes. The Crisis of Democratic Representation in the Andes addresses an important question for Latin America as well as other parts of the world: Why does representation sometimes fail to work?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aDemocracyzAndes Region. 0aPolitical culturezAndes Region. 0aRepresentative government and representationzAndes Region. 4aLatin American Studies. 4aPolitics -- Comparative and International Politics. 4aPolitics -- Latin America. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Political Parties.2bisacsh1 aBejarano, Ana María, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBejarano, Ana María, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCrisp, Brian F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeongómez, Eduardo Pizarro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeongómez, Eduardo Pizarro, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLevine, Daniel H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMainwaring, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMainwaring, Scott, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMayorga, René Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4ht